Creating secrets.

Secrets use the same three creation methods as a config map, plus a few secret specific shortcuts.

From literals. You use kubectl create secret generic and pass each value with the from literal flag, naming the username and password right on the command line.

From files. You point the from file flag at a path. This is handy for binary or large values, like a private key, where typing the contents would be impractical.

From a tee-el-ess certificate and key pair. There is a typed shortcut, kubectl create secret tls, where you pass the certificate and the key, and kubernetes builds a tee-el-ess typed secret for you.

From a registry credential. Another typed shortcut, kubectl create secret docker registry, takes the registry server, username, and password, and builds the credential a node needs to pull private images. We come back to that shortly.

And declaratively. You write the yaml directly, using either data or string data. While you are authoring, prefer string data, because you can type the raw value and let the ay-pee-eye server base sixty four encode it on write.

One precedence rule to remember. If both data and string data are set, and the same key appears in each, string data wins. That is useful when you are patching an existing secret and want your raw value to override the encoded one.
